Command        Description                                       Example
-----------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
top            View real-time system performance.                top
htop           Enhanced `top` with a user-friendly interface.    sudo apt-get install htop; htop
vmstat         View system processes, memory, paging, block IO,  vmstat 2
               and CPU activity.
mpstat         Report CPU-related statistics.                    sudo apt-get install sysstat; mpstat
sar            Collect and report system activity information.   sar -u 1 3
free           Display free and used memory.                     free -h
cat /proc/meminfo Detailed memory usage information.             cat /proc/meminfo
df             Report file system disk space usage.              df -h
du             Estimate file space usage.                        du -sh /path/to/directory
iostat         Report CPU and I/O statistics.                    sudo apt-get install sysstat; iostat
ifconfig       Display network interfaces.                       ifconfig
ip             More powerful alternative to ifconfig.            ip a
netstat        Display network connections, routing tables,      netstat -tulnp
               and interface statistics.
ss             Investigate sockets.                              ss -tuln
ping           Check connectivity to a host.                     ping google.com
traceroute     Trace the route packets take to a network host.   traceroute google.com
ps             Report a snapshot of current processes.           ps aux
pstree         Display running processes as a tree.              pstree
lsof           List open files.                                  lsof
dmesg          Print the message buffer of the kernel.           dmesg | less
journalctl     Query and display logs from systemd journal.      journalctl -xe
tail           Output the last part of files (useful for log     tail -f /var/log/syslog
               files).
